  "prompt": "Can a Greek question mark (;) be used instead of a semicolon (;) in a programming language such as C#, Java or Pascal?",
  "response": "No, a Greek question mark (;) cannot be used in place of a semicolon (;) in programming languages such as C#, Java, or Pascal. In these languages, the semicolon has a specific syntactic role, typically used to terminate statements. The Greek question mark (which visually resembles a semicolon in English) is treated as a distinct Unicode character and does not have the same syntactic significance in these programming languages. Therefore, using it instead of a semicolon would result in syntax errors and would not be interpreted correctly by the compiler or interpreter.",
